oyal Succession in Heroic Greece -- t20. Odysseus and the Genus ‘Hero’ -- t21. Patterns of Human Error in Homer -- t22. Timē and Aretē in Homer -- t23. Homer and the Bottomless Well of the Past -- t24. Greece in the Eighth Century BCE and the ‘Renaissance’ Phenomenon -- tPart IV: Transmission and Reception -- t25. Ajax’s Entry in the Hesiodic Catalogue of Women -- t26. The Cypria, the Iliad, and the Problem of Multiformity in Oral and Written Tradition -- t27. Homer as a Foundation Text -- t28. ‘She Turns about in the Same Spot and Watches for Orion’: ancient criticism and exegesis of Od. 5.274 = Il. 18.488 -- t29. Regional Texts and the Circulation of Books: The Case of Homer -- t30. Canonizing and Decanonizing Homer: Reception of the Homeric Poems in Antiquity and Modernity -- t31. Homer at the Panathenaia: Some possible Scenarios -- tReferences -- tGeneral index -- tIndex of passages cited0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection includes thirty scholarly essays on Homer and Greek epic poetry published by Margalit Finkelberg over the past three decades. The topics discussed reflect the author’s research interests and represent the main directions of her contribution to Homeric studies: Homer's language and diction, archaic Greek epic tradition, Homer's world and values, transmission and reception of the Homeric poems. The book gives special emphasis to some of the central issues in contemporary Homeric scholarship, such as oral-formulaic theory and the role of the individual poet; Neoanalysis and the character of the relationship between Homer and the tradition about the Trojan War; the multi-layered texture of the Homeric poems; the Homeric Question; the canonic status of the Iliad and the Odyssey in antiquity and modernity. All the articles are revised and updated. The book addresses both scholars and advanced students of Classics, as well as non-specialists interested in the Homeric poems and their journey through centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEpic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticism. 4aGriechische Literatur. 4aHomer. 4aHomerische Frage. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aHomeric Question.  aNeoanalysis.  aoral-formulaic theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2019 Englishz978311061009308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2019z9783110605945oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831106715200 cprintz978311067142140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311067145240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110671452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110671452.jpg  a978-3-11-061009-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-069627-1  DG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1b2020  a978-3-11-069628-8  DG Ebook Package English 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2019  aZDB-23-DGGb2019